        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="hover:text-white/70">Pallet Conveyors</a>
        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <span class="text-white/70">Pallet Dispensers</span>
      </nav>
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <div class="section-label text-accent-bright/80 mb-6">Pallet Conveyors</div>
        <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-wide uppercase leading-[0.95] mb-8">
          Pallet Dispensers &#x26; <span class="text-accent-bright">Destackers</span>
        </h1>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article>
    <section class="py-12 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="aio-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <p id="aio-heading" class="text-lg text-ink leading-relaxed">
          A pallet dispenser (destacker) automatically separates individual empty pallets from a stack and feeds them onto a conveyor leading to a palletizer. Magazine-style dispensers use lift forks or scissor mechanisms to isolate the bottom pallet; inline dispensers integrate directly into the pallet conveyor for continuous flow; robotic dispensers use articulated arms to handle mixed pallet sizes and damaged pallets. Manufacturers like Columbia Machine, Ouellette Machinery, Whallon Machinery, and SCOTT Automation supply pallet dispensers for automated <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">palletizing lines</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ HOW PALLET DISPENSERS WORK ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="how-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Fundamentals</div>
        <h2 id="how-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          How Pallet Dispensers <span class="text-accent">Work</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            A pallet dispenser operates in a repeating cycle: hold a stack of empty pallets, separate the bottom (or top) pallet from the stack, and discharge the single pallet onto a conveyor. The cycle takes 8-15 seconds for mechanical dispensers and 5-10 seconds for high-speed models. The palletizer signals the dispenser when it needs a new empty pallet , the dispenser responds by cycling one pallet onto the outfeed conveyor.
          </p>
          <p>
            The separation mechanism is the critical design element. Pallets interlock, stick together (especially new wood pallets), and vary in height and condition. The separation mechanism must reliably isolate one pallet from the stack without jamming, even with damaged or non-standard pallets.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Bottom-Dispensing Mechanism</h3>
          <p>
            Bottom-dispensing is the most common design. Fork-style fingers engage the second pallet from the bottom, lifting the stack. The bottom pallet rests on the conveyor surface. The conveyor advances, pulling the bottom pallet out from under the stack. The stack then lowers onto the conveyor, and the cycle repeats for the next pallet. Fork fingers retract and engage pneumatically or servo-driven.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Top-Dispensing Mechanism</h3>
          <p>
            Top-dispensing lifts the entire stack, removes the top pallet, and places it on the outfeed conveyor. This design is less common for standard palletizing but useful when pallet quality is poor (damaged bottom pallets cause jams in bottom-dispensing systems). Robotic dispensers typically work top-down , the robot grips the top pallet and transfers it.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ DISPENSER TYPES ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="types-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Types</div>
        <h2 id="types-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Pallet Dispenser <span class="text-accent">Types</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-4">Magazine-Style Dispensers</h3>
          <p>
            Magazine-style dispensers hold a single stack of 10-20 pallets inside a vertical frame (the magazine). A forklift loads a full pallet stack into the magazine from the side or rear. The dispenser cycles pallets from the bottom of the stack onto the outfeed conveyor. When the stack empties, the forklift loads a new stack.
          </p>
          <p>
            Magazine dispensers are the most common and cost-effective type. They suit operations running one pallet size at consistent volumes. The magazine frame constrains pallet size , changing pallet dimensions requires manual adjustment of the magazine width and depth guides. Columbia Machine and Ouellette Machinery supply magazine-style dispensers. <!-- VERIFY: Current product names for Columbia Machine and Ouellette dispensers -->
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-10 mb-4">Inline Dispensers</h3>
          <p>
            Inline dispensers integrate directly into the <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">pallet conveyor</a> line. Pallet stacks arrive on the conveyor, the dispenser separates individual pallets, and single pallets continue downstream to the palletizer. No separate loading step , the forklift places pallet stacks on the infeed conveyor, and the dispenser processes them in sequence.
          </p>
          <p>
            Inline dispensers suit high-volume operations where continuous pallet flow matters. They eliminate the stop-and-load cycle of magazine dispensers. However, they require more conveyor infrastructure (infeed conveyor for stacks, outfeed conveyor for singles, and accumulation for stack staging).
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-10 mb-4">Robotic Dispensers</h3>
          <p>
            Robotic pallet dispensers use articulated arm robots (FANUC, ABB, KUKA) to grip individual pallets from a stack and place them on the outfeed conveyor. The robot's vision system or fixed sensors detect the top pallet's position and height. The gripper , typically a clamping fork or vacuum pad system , grips the pallet and transfers it.
          </p>
          <p>
            Robotic dispensers handle mixed pallet sizes without mechanical changeover. The robot adapts grip position and place coordinates through recipe selection. They also tolerate damaged, warped, or non-standard pallets better than mechanical dispensers because the robot's force sensing detects stuck pallets and adjusts force accordingly. Cost is higher ($$$$) but justified for high-mix operations or facilities handling multiple pallet types (GMA 48x40, EUR 1200x800, custom sizes).
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ COMPARISON TABLE ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="compare-heading">
      <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Comparison</div>
        <h2 id="compare-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-10">
          Dispenser Type <span class="text-accent">Comparison</span>
        </h2>
