          <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse min-w-[850px]">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b-2 border-ink">
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Type</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Capacity</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Cycle Time</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Pallet Flexibility</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4">Relative Cost</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-base text-ink-muted">
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Magazine-style</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">10-20 pallets</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">8-15 sec</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Single size (manual changeover)</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Inline</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">Continuous</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">6-12 sec</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Single size (auto-adjust available)</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Robotic</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">Stack-dependent</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">5-10 sec</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Multiple sizes (recipe-based)</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$$</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ PALLET TYPES ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="pallet-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Pallet Compatibility</div>
        <h2 id="pallet-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Pallet Types &#x26; <span class="text-accent">Dispenser Compatibility</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Pallet dispensers must handle the specific pallet type used in your operation. Pallet material, size, and condition affect dispenser design and reliability:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Wood GMA pallets (48 x 40 in):</strong> The most common pallet in North America. New wood pallets interlock tightly and require higher separation force. Recycled pallets vary in height and condition , broken boards, protruding nails, and warped decks cause mechanical dispenser jams.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Plastic pallets:</strong> Consistent dimensions and weight. Nest tightly when stacked. Some designs include anti-nesting features (bumps or offsets) that aid mechanical separation. Easier to dispense than wood pallets.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">EUR pallets (1200 x 800 mm):</strong> Standard in Europe. Four-way entry. Dispenser magazine requires adjustment from GMA dimensions.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Custom/industrial pallets:</strong> Oversized, undersized, or non-standard pallets require custom dispenser sizing. Robotic dispensers adapt most easily to custom pallet dimensions.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Pallet quality is the largest reliability variable. Operations using recycled wood pallets should budget for higher dispenser maintenance and consider inline pallet inspection (photoeye or vision-based) to reject damaged pallets before they enter the dispenser. For a full discussion of <a href="/industries/warehouse-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">warehouse and distribution conveyor systems</a>, see our dedicated guide.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ CONVEYOR INTEGRATION ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="integration-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Integration</div>
        <h2 id="integration-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Conveyor <span class="text-accent">Integration</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            The pallet dispenser connects to the palletizing system through pallet conveyors , typically <a href="/conveyor-types/cdlr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">chain-driven live roller (CDLR)</a> or chain conveyor rated for 2,500+ lb loads. The conveyor carries individual pallets from the dispenser to the palletizer load station. Key integration points:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Pallet centering:</strong> Guide rails or centering devices on the outfeed conveyor align the pallet before it reaches the palletizer. Misaligned pallets cause stacking errors.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Pallet presence detection:</strong> Photoeye sensors confirm a pallet is in position at the palletizer before the palletizer cycles. The dispenser feeds the next pallet only when the previous pallet has cleared.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Stack height management:</strong> The dispenser PLC tracks the number of pallets remaining in the stack and signals for a refill (forklift alert, tower light, or SCADA notification) when the count reaches a threshold (typically 3-5 pallets remaining).</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Slip sheet dispensing:</strong> Some palletizer systems require a slip sheet (corrugated or plastic) between the pallet and the first layer of cases. A slip sheet dispenser works alongside the pallet dispenser, placing a sheet on each empty pallet before it reaches the palletizer.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            For more on end-of-line conveyor integration including <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/case/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">case packing</a>, sealing, and palletizing, see our packaging line conveyor guides. For cost considerations, see the <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor cost guide</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a pallet dispenser?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>A pallet dispenser (destacker) automatically separates individual empty pallets from a stack and feeds them to a <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">palletizer conveyor</a>. Stores 10-20 pallets per stack. Eliminates manual pallet placement for continuous palletizer operation.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            Dispenser vs. destacker?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>The terms are interchangeable. Both refer to a machine that separates individual pallets from a stack. No industry-standard distinction exists between the two terms.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How many pallets can a dispenser hold?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Standard magazine dispensers hold 10-20 pallets per stack (80-120 inches of stack height). Multi-stack magazine dispensers hold 20-80 pallets. Higher capacity reduces refill frequency for high-speed lines.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What types of pallet dispensers are available?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Magazine-style ($$, single stack, bottom-dispensing), inline ($$$, continuous flow, integrates into pallet conveyor), and robotic ($$$$, handles mixed pallet sizes, recipe-based changeover). Magazine-style is most common for standard operations.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
